Yes, these three details (class, method, outcome) are captured in each metric logging statement within PcapMultiCacheableAdvice.java. Here’s where they are included:


---

1️⃣ The Class on Which the Caching Happened

📍 Captured using:

pjp.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName()

📍 Where it appears:

In every Metrics.counter() call:

Metrics.counter(CACHE_HIT_METRIC, 
                "class", pjp.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName(),
                "method", pjp.getSignature().getName(),
                "outcome", "hit").increment();



---

2️⃣ The Method in Which the Caching Happens

📍 Captured using:

pjp.getSignature().getName()

📍 Where it appears:

In every Metrics.counter() call:

Metrics.counter(CACHE_MISS_METRIC, 
                "class", pjp.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName(),
                "method", pjp.getSignature().getName(),
                "outcome", "miss").increment();



---

3️⃣ The Outcome of the Caching (Success/Failure)

📍 Captured as "hit", "miss", "failure", "eviction.failure", "data.mismatch", "store"
📍 Where it appears:

Cache Hit: "outcome", "hit"

Cache Miss: "outcome", "miss"

Cache Failure: "outcome", "failure"

Eviction Failure: "outcome", "eviction.failure"

Data Mismatch Warning: "outcome", "data.mismatch"

Cache Store: "outcome", "store"


📍 Example in Metrics.counter() calls:

Metrics.counter(CACHE_FAILURE_METRIC, 
                "class", pjp.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName(),
                "method", pjp.getSignature().getName(),
                "outcome", "failure").increment();


---

📌 Final Confirmation

✅ The class is captured via pjp.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName().
✅ The method is captured via pjp.getSignature().getName().
✅ The outcome is explicitly set in each Metrics.counter() call.

This ensures all three required details are included in the DataDog metrics.

